#: ../en/docs/filters.md:28
msgid "The above snippet calls the template function `M:q.llink()` with two named\n"
"arguments `name` and `lingua`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:31
msgid ""
"All of these arguments specify conditions that a document must fulfill to\n"
"pass the filter.  In the above case that would be documents whose `name`\n"
"variable has the same value as the current document, and the `lingua`\n"
"variable should have the hard-coded value `de`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:36
msgid "## Broken and Ambiguous Links"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:38
msgid ""
"If you specify a filter that produces no results, you will normally see a warning\n"
"in the console. Likewise, for methods that should produce exactly one hit,\n"
"you will get a warning if more than one matching document exists."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:42
msgid "Such functions are `M:q.link()`, `M:q.anchor()`, and `M:q.xref()` and their\n"
"multilanguage equivalents `M:q.llink()`, `M:q.lanchor()`, and `M:q.lxref()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:45
msgid "## Conditions"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:47
msgid "The equality check is the default condition for filters but there are more\n"
"at your disposal with a slightly more complicated syntax:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:50
msgid ""
"```tt2\n"
"See the [API docs]([% q.link(name='api-docs') %]).\n"
"See the [API docs]([% q.link(name=['eq', 'api-docs']) %]).\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:55
msgid ""
"The second example uses the advanced syntax. Instead of a single value,\n"
"you specify a list of two values.  The first one is the comparison operator,\n"
"and the second one the value."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:59
msgid "In fact both lines do exactly the same, because `eq` as the default\n"
"comparison operator."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:62
msgid "So, the advanced syntax is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:64
msgid ""
"```tt2\n"
"VARIABLE=[OPERATOR, VALUE]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:72
msgid "Returns true if the values are string-wise equal."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:78
msgid "Returns true if the values are string-wise not equal."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:84
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is (string-wise) greater or equal than the value specified. For example \"bbb\" is string-wise greater than \"aaa\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:90
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is (string-wise) greater than the value specified. For example \"bbb\" is string-wise greater than \"aaa\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:96
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is (string-wise) less or equal than the value specified. For example \"aaa\" is string-wise less than \"bbb\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:102
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is (string-wise) less than the value specified. For example \"aaa\" is string-wise less than \"bbb\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:108
msgid "Like [`eq`](#eq) but ignores case for the comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:114
msgid "Like [`ne`](#ne) but ignores case for the comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:120
msgid "Like [`ge`](#ge) but ignores case for the comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:126
msgid "Like [`gt`](#gt) but ignores case for the comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:132
msgid "Like [`le`](#le) but ignores case for the comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:138
msgid "Like [`lt`](#lt) but ignores case for the comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:144
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is numerically equal to the value specified.\n"
"For example `1.0` and `1` and `+1` are all numerically equal."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:151
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is numerically not equal to the value specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:157
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is numerically greater or equal than the value specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:163
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is numerically greater than the value specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:169
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is numerically less or equal than the value specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:175
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is numerically less than the value specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:181
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document matches the value specified as a Perl regular expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:187
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document does not match the value specified as a Perl regular expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:193
msgid "Returns true if the value of the variable in the other document is an array (a list) the value specified is contained in that array."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:199
msgid "Like [`contains`](#contains) but case is ignored for the comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:201
msgid "## Filtering Results are Cached"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/filters.md:203
msgid ""
"Applying filters to a large set of documents is potentially expensive. However,\n"
"you pay the price only once. All results of filtering operations are cached\n"
"in memory, even when you shuffle the order of the conditions in the filter."
