#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:2
msgctxt "title"
msgid "Output Location"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:6
msgctxt "description"
msgid "Learn how input locations are translated to output locations in Qgoda."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:8
msgid ""
"Please note that determining the output location for assets differs\n"
"significantly from other systems for example Jekyll.  Whereas in Jekyll you\n"
"normally set the permalink of an asset, in Qgoda you normally set the \n"
"output path and the permalink is computed from the path.  The result is\n"
"very similar but maybe more flexible."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:14
msgid ""
"By default, an asset's location is simply preserved.  That means if you have an\n"
"asset `{srcdir}/assets/images/logo.jpeg` it will be copied to\n"
"`{sitedir}/assets/images/logo.jpeg`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:20
msgid "## Path Translation"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:22
msgid ""
"Processed assets are subject to path translation.  Their relative path to\n"
"the site directory is by default modified.  With the default configuration\n"
"the asset `{srcdir}/pages/en/about-qgoda.htm` would end up as \n"
"`{sitedir}/pages/en/about-qgoda/index.htm` and the markdown input file\n"
"`{srcdir}/posts/en/version-0.2-released.md` would end up as\n"
"`{sitedir}/posts/en/version-0.2-released/index.html`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:29
msgid "For the gory details of the process, let's take the input location \n"
"`{srcdir}/posts/en/version-0.2-released.md` as an example."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:32
msgid "The starting point is the relative path to the source directory\n"
"`/posts/en/version-0.2-released.md` which has the following components:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:35
msgid ""
"<dl>\n"
"  <dt>posts/en</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The directory portion.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>version-0.2-released</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The basename, that is the filename portion without the suffix or suffixes.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>md</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The suffix or filename extension.</dd>\n"
"</dl>"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:44
msgid ""
"By default the output location of a document in Qgoda relative to the \n"
"configured site directory is\n"
"`{directory}/{basename}/{index}.{suffix}`.  The variable `index`\n"
"has the default value \"index\" which is no coincidence but the default value\n"
"used by all common web servers."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:50
msgid "## Suffix Translation"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:52
msgid ""
"Asset processing is triggered by the suffixes of the source file.  The triggers\n"
"are defined in the variable `C:processors.triggers` in the site configuration\n"
"file `P:_config.yaml`.  Look at this excerpt of the Qgoda default configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:56
msgid ""
"```yaml\n"
"processors:\n"
"    triggers:\n"
"        md: markdown\n"
"        html: html\n"
"        htm: html\n"
"    chains:\n"
"        markdown:\n"
"            modules: [Markdown, HTML]\n"
"            suffix: html\n"
"            wrapper: html\n"
"        html:\n"
"            modules: HTML\n"
"   modules:\n"
"       Markdown: Markdown\n"
"       HTML: Template::Toolkit\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:74
msgid ""
"The suffix `md` triggers the processor chain `markdown`.  This chain\n"
"has configured an output suffix `html`.  The translated filename of the\n"
"output file is therefore not `index.md` but `index.html`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:78
msgid "The processor chain `html` does *not* define an output suffix.  The suffix is \n"
"therefore left untouched."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:81
msgid "## Multiple Suffixes"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:83
msgid ""
"A filename can have multiple suffixes, for example \n"
"`what-is-qgoda.md.utf8.fr`.  This is useful for content negotiation as\n"
"implemented in the popular Apache web server.  When doing suffix translation,\n"
"Qgoda translates the rightmost suffix.  The example filename would therefore\n"
"be translated into `what-is-qgoda/index.md.utf8.fr`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:89
msgid ""
"It is also important to note that all suffixes are considered for processor \n"
"chain selection.  The rightmost suffix \"wins\".  If you have a filename\n"
"`example.html.md` the markdown processor chain will be selected because\n"
"`md` is right of `html`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:94
msgid "## Gory Details of Suffix Parsing"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:96
msgid ""
"You may have noticed in one the above example the filename \n"
"`version-0.2-released.md` which gets translated into \n"
"`version-0.2-released/index.md`.  Obviously only `md` is considered a suffix\n"
"and `2-released` is not."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:101
msgid ""
"Qgoda's notion of a suffix is a string of one or more alphanumerical\n"
"characters.  Since `2-released` contains a hyphen, it is not considered\n"
"a suffix."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:105
msgid ""
"Suffixes are extracted right to left, stopping at the first false positive.\n"
"Take `version-0.22.beta-released.utf8.en.md` as a rather esoteric example.\n"
"The software would consider `md`, `en`, `utf8` suffixes and stop then\n"
"because `beta-released` contains a non-alphanumerical character.  Although\n"
"`22` (before the string \"beta\") contains only alphanumerical characters\n"
"because the suffix extraction had already stopped."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:112
msgid "## Permalinks"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:114
msgid ""
"Permalinks are computed from the output location.  By default, they are \n"
"simply the relative path to the site directory.  If the filename portion\n"
"of the output location matches the configured index string (normally\n"
"\"index\") followed by one or more suffixes the filename is stripped off."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:119
msgid "For example `posts/en/about-qgoda/index.utf8.md` would be translated into\n"
"the permalink `/posts/en/about-qgoda/`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:122
msgid "## Customization"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:124
msgid ""
"You can fully customize both output location and permalinks by setting the\n"
"variables `C:location` or `C:permalink` respectively in the front matter of an\n"
"asset, as a default for a certain directory or site wide in `C:_config.yaml`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:128
msgid ""
"You can interpolate all kinds of asset variables into the configured string\n"
"by placing them inside {curly} braces.  For example the default configuration\n"
"for the variable `C:location` is `/{directory}/{basename}/{config.index}.{suffix}`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:132
msgid "The following variables are meaningful for location and permalink \n"
"customization:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:135
msgid ""
"<dl>\n"
"  <dt>path</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The absolute path of the asset.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>relpath</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The relative path of the asset, without a leading slash.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>directory</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The directory portion of \"path\" without a leading or trailing slash.  \n"
"      This will be the empty string for assets in the top-level source\n"
"      directory.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>filename</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The current filename</dd>\n"
"  <dt>basename</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The basename portion of the filename (without suffix/suffixes).</dd>\n"
"  <dt>suffix</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The suffix (resp. suffixes) with a leading dot, subject to translation.\n"
"      If there are no suffixes the variable does not exist.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>config</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The site configuration as read from \"_config.yaml\"</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The date of the asset.  Do not use directly but one of the\n"
"      subkeys below.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.epoch</dt>\n"
"  <dd>Seconds since the Epoch (00:00:00 UTC, January 1, 1970)</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.year</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The four-digit year.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.month</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The two-digit month (01-12).</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.imonth</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The month (1-12) without the leading zero.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.mday</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The two-digit day of the month (01-31).</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.imday</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The day of the month (1-31) without the leading zero.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.day</dt>\n"
"  <dd>A synonym for \"date.mday\".</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.iday</dt>\n"
"  <dd>A synonym for \"date.imday\".</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.hour</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The hour of the day (01-24).</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.ihour</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The hour of the day (1-24) without the leading zero.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.hour12</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The hour of the day (01-12) on a 12-hour clock.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.ihour12</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The hour of the day (1-12) on a 12-hour clock without the leading zero.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.ampm</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The national representation of either \"ante meridiem\"\n"
"      (a.m.)  or \"post meridiem\" (p.m.)  as appropriate.  This can be\n"
"      an empty string, depending on the currently selected locale.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.min</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The minutes (01-59).</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.imin</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The minutes (1-59) without the leading zero.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.sec</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The seconds (01-60).</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.isec</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The seconds (1-60) without the leading zero.</dd>\n"
"  <dt>date.dst</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The string \"DST\" (may be translated!) if Daylight Savings Time is in use</dd>\n"
"  <dt>location</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The computed location of the document.  Before the location is computed,\n"
"      the variable is a synonym for \"path\".</dd>\n"
"  <dt>permalink</dt>\n"
"  <dd>The computed permalink of the document.  Before the permalink is computed,\n"
"      the variable is a synonym for `location`.</dd>\n"
"</dl>"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:202
msgid "Note that variables are not necessarily plain old strings but can be more\n"
"complicated.  Take this example configuration in YAML:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:205
msgid ""
"```yaml\n"
"dictionary:\n"
"    foo: 1 # dictionary.foo\n"
"    bar: 2 # dictionary['bar']\n"
"    baz: 3 # dictionary[\"baz\"]\n"
"array:\n"
"    - Tom    # array[0]\n"
"    - Dick   # array.1 also works.\n"
"    - Harry  # array['2'], you can also use double quotes.\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/output-location.md:216
msgid "Quoted strings have JavaScript semantics!"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:2
msgctxt "title"
msgid "Pagination"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:6
msgctxt "description"
msgid "How to distribute listings over multiple pages."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:8
msgid "Functions for paginating listings are often very complicated and limited\n"
"in other systems. Pagination in Qgoda is a no-brainer."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:13
msgid "## General Idea"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:15
msgid "Pagination consist of two tasks:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:17
msgid ""
"1. Cut the set of documents for the current page of the listing out of the\n"
"   collection of all documents\n"
"2. Compute the data for the previous and next page, the total number of pages\n"
"   and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:22
msgid "Number 2 is 3rd grade math, number 1 can give serious headaches."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:24
msgid ""
"In Qgoda, the automatic creation of another page is very simple. The\n"
"template function `M:q.clone()` does exactly that: It creates an exact\n"
"copy of the current page and just modifies values that you specify in\n"
"the call to it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:92
msgid "This will produce a complete listing with pagination."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:94
msgid ""
"Line 2 creates a sorted collection of all posts of your site, most recent\n"
"first. See [@ q.lanchor(name = 'listings') @] if you want to create a listing\n"
"of pages from a certain date rage, from a certain category, pages containing\n"
"a tag or a combination thereof."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:99
msgid ""
"In line 4 the variable `start` gets initialized from the document variable\n"
"`asset.start`. It is the (zero-based) index of the first document shown\n"
"on this page of the listing. Initially it is `null` which is fine because\n"
"it evaluates to 0. Still in line 4, the document variable `asset.start`\n"
"is reset to 0. Ths is not important here but when you create listings of\n"
"tags, where you will have clones of cloned documents."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:106
msgid ""
"Line 5 contains the call to `M:q.paginate()` which is documented below. You\n"
"pass it at list the named argument `total` that contains the total number\n"
"of pages and `start` which contains the (zero-based) index of the first\n"
"document in the collection on *this* page. The function returns an object\n"
"which contains all information that you need for creating a pagination over\n"
"the listing pages."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:113
msgid ""
"Lines 7-11 just contain a minimal listing of a paged subset of the current\n"
"page. See in line 8, how that subset is created. The method\n"
"[`splice()`](http://www.template-toolkit.org/docs/manual/VMethods.html#method_splice)\n"
"cuts out those documents from the collection that should be displayed on\n"
"this page. The first argument is the (zero-based) index of the first document,\n"
"the second one is the number of documents you want."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:120
msgid "For both arguments you simply use the values `p.start` and `p.per_page` that\n"
"you have received from the call to `M:q.paginate()` above."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:123
msgid "Below that, the pagination navigation begins. In line 15 we create a link\n"
"to the previous listing simply by using the path from `p.previous_link`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:126
msgid "Lines 17-23 loop over all listing pages, link to them, und use the\n"
"precomputed array `p.links` as the link targets."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:129
msgid "Line 25 is like line 15, but creates the link to the next listing page."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:131
msgid ""
"The actual magic happens in lines 27-29. Iff there are more documents to\n"
"display, a copy of the current listing page is created with\n"
"`M:q.clone()`. The clone is an exact copy of the current page. Only two\n"
"properties are overwritten."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:136
msgid ""
"One is the `V:asset.location` of the clone which is precomputed as something\n"
"like `index-3.html` for the third listing so that the copy will not overwrite\n"
"the current page."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:140
msgid "The other one is our variable `start` which will contain the starting\n"
"document of this page plus the number of documents displayed on this page."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:143
msgid "In other words: The listing creates a copy of itself with the next starting\n"
"document, until all documents have been displayed."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:146
msgid ""
"That's it! In reality, you may notice that this example has a couple of flaws.\n"
"For example, the links to the previous and next page should only be\n"
"displayed, when there actually *is* a previous or next page. You will also\n"
"want to style the navigation and may add aria-attributes but that's just\n"
"template code."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:152
msgid ""
"You can take a\n"
"[full-fledged example](https://github.com/gflohr/qgoda-multilang/blob/master/_views/components/listing.html)\n"
"from the [Qgoda Multilanguage Theme](https://github.com/gflohr/qgoda-multilang)\n"
"as a starting point for your own listing and pagination module."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:157
msgid "## The `q.clone()` Method"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:159
msgid ""
"This method creates an identical copy of the current document. Its usage is\n"
"not limited to pagination. You use it whenever you have to dynamically create\n"
"documents. Another typical use case are tag listings, where you clone the\n"
"listing for the current tag, so that you can create a listing for the next\n"
"tag, until there are no more tags."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:165
msgid "A typical usage looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:176
msgid "Whatever named arguments you pass, will become (changed) variables of the\n"
"cloned document."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:179
msgid ""
"Simply creating clones of the current document would lead to an endless loop,\n"
"where each clone would overwrite its parent with an identical copy. You\n"
"therefore have to adhere to two rules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:183
msgid ""
"1. Always put the call to `q.clone()` into an `[% IF %]` directive that will\n"
"at one point yield a false value.\n"
"2. You *must* override the `V:asset.location` property of the clone so that\n"
"it will not overwrite the current document."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:188
msgid ""
"The rules are simple but you will notice sooner or later that they are easy\n"
"to forget. If you have the impression that you have created an endless loop,\n"
"re-run qgoda with the option `--verbose` to better understand what is going\n"
"on."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:193
msgid "## The `q.paginate()` Method"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:195
msgid ""
"The `M:q.paginate()` template function only performs some simple\n"
"computations that helps you create the navigation for the listing pages\n"
"in HTML. It could also be implemented with Template Toolkit functions,\n"
"only that this would be slower and more complicted."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:200
#: ../en/news/client-side-syntax-highlighting.md:210
msgid "### Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:212
msgid ""
"The actual call is done in line 5. But you typically invoke it with two\n"
"named arguments `total` (total number of items) and `start` (index of the\n"
"first item)."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:216
msgid ""
"Therefore you normally create a collection of documents like in line 3. See\n"
"[@ q.lanchor(name='listings') @] for details about that. The size of that\n"
"collection is then used for the argument `total`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:220
msgid ""
"The other argument that you normally need is `start`. It defaults to 0.\n"
"For subsequent listings that were created with\n"
"[`q.clone()`](#the-q.clone-method) you increase\n"
"this parameter by the number of documents (resp. items) shown in the\n"
"current listing."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:226
msgid "### Input Parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:228
msgid "The following named arguments are supported:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:230
msgid "#### `total`"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:232
msgid "The total number of items, resp. the size of the collection. This argument\n"
"is mandatory and must be greater than zero."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:235
msgid "#### `start`"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:237
msgid "The first item that is displayed in the current listing. The count starts\n"
"at zero not at one!"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:240
msgid "If omitted, this parameter defaults to zero."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:242
msgid "#### `per_page`"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:244
msgid "The number of items that are displayed on one page. Defaults to 10."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:246
msgid "#### `stem`"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:248
msgid ""
"The filename stem used for creating subsequent listings. Defaults to the\n"
"basename without extender of the original document. If the original document\n"
"has the file name `index.html`, the stem defaults to `index`, and the\n"
"subsequent listing pages will be saved as `index-2.html`, `index-3.html`,\n"
"and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:254
msgid "#### `extender`"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:256
msgid ""
"The extender used for creating subsequent listings. Defaults to the extender\n"
"of the current document.  The extender has to include a possible leading\n"
"dot! You must use `.html`,  not `html`."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:260
msgid "### Output"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:262
msgid "The returned value is an object, a hash with the following properties:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/pagination.md:264
msgid ""
"| Property/Key  | Value                                                       |\n"
"| ------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| start         | Where the next listing should start. This is the last starting point plus the number of items per page.\n"
"| page          | The page number of the current page. The count starts at 1. |\n"
"| page0         | The zero-based page number of the current page. That is `page` minus 1.\n"
"| per_page      | The number of items per page.  That just echoes the corresponding input parameter.\n"
"| total_pages   | The total number of pages needed to display all items.\n"
"| previous_link | A link to the previous page or `null/undef` if this is the first page.\n"
"| next_link     | A link to the next page or `null/undef` if this is the last page.\n"
"| links         | An array of links to all listing pages. This will be something like `['index.html', 'index-2.html', 'index-3.html', 'index-4.html']\n"
"| tabindices    | This will be [0, 0, -1, 0] is this is listing page number 3 of 4 pages in total. You can use the corresponding value for the `tabindex` attribute of the corresponding `a` anchor linking to that page.\n"
"| tabindexes    | The same as `tabindices` if you prefer that spelling.\n"
"| next_start    | If you call `M:q.clone()`, use this as the `start` property of the cloned listing.\n"
"| next_location | If you use `M:q.clone()`, use this as the `location` property of the cloned listing."
msgstr ""

